<para>Field collection: 

The Kingston station is visited once every two weeks during the ice-free season (usually 
April through December). The other five cardinal survey stations are visited approximately four 
times each year, generally in April, June, August, and October. 

During each visit physical variables are measured and water samples are collected. 
Temperature and oxygen concentration are measured 0.5 meters below the waterâs surface using a YSI field oxygen probe. Light is measured using a Licor spherical quantum sensor, in the air and 0.5, 1.0, and 2.0 meters below the waterâs surface. Secchi depth is also measured. Current flow is also measured using a wooden current cross. Water samples are collected from 0.5 meters below the waterâs surface using a peristaltic pump. Zooplankton samples are also collected; one set (microzooplankton, in triplicate, used to enumerate rotifers, nauplii, veligers and tintinnid ciliates) using the peristaltic pump and a 35 Âµm mesh plankton net, and a second set (macrozooplankton, in triplicate, used to enumerate copepods and cladocerans) using a calibrated open-diaphragm bilge pump and a 73 Âµm mesh plankton net. The concentrated zooplankton samples are treated with carbonated water (used as a narcotizing agent) and then preserved in a buffered 4&#37; formaldehyde solution (60 grams of sucrose per liter and 8.4 grams of sodium bicarbonate per liter) to yield a final formaldehyde concentration of 2&#37;. A 19 milliliter whole water sample is preserved in 1 milliliter of 20&#37; buffered formaldehyde (30 grams of sodium borate per liter) for enumeration of bacterial abundance using the acridine orange direct count method. A field-filtered, sulfuric acid preserved, sample (in triplicate) is also collected for DOC analysis. 

Lab Analyses: 

The whole water samples collected are used for the following lab analyses. 

Seston; dry weight and organic matter (in triplicate from each of three bottles) 

Water is filtered onto pre-combusted Whatman 934-AH filters which are dried at 70 degrees 
centigrade for at least 12 hours before being weighed, then combusted at 450 degrees centigrade for four hours and then weighed again. 

Chlorophyll concentration; (in triplicate) 

Water is filtered onto Whatman GFF filters which are frozen until a basic methanol extraction is performed and the samples are measured using a Turner Designs fluorometer. 

DIC and DOC concentration; (in triplicate) 

Water is filtered through Whatman 934-AH pre-combusted filters and refrigerated until analysis 
using a Shimadzu high-temperature combustion organic carbon analyzer. The field-preserved 
DOC samples are also run using the Shimadzu analyzer and occasionally whole water samples 
are analyzed using a Shimadzu gas chromatograph for comparison with the carbon analyzer. 

Water chemistry; total nitrogen, total phosphorus, ammonia, nitrate, and phosphate 

Bacterial production; Tritiated thymidine method 

pH; duplicate samples measured using lab pH meter 

Turbidity; duplicate samples measured using bench-top nephelometer 

Phytoplankton; a one liter sample is preserved using Lugolâs solution 

Zooplankton; formaldehyde-preserved samples are counted using both a dissecting microscope 
and an inverted microscope 
